commit_message:
Introduce docs and reproducible examples (#28)

* Add PostgreSQL example/docs

1. Add a reproducible docker-compose.
2. Move the docs from README to a separate docs page referencing the
reproducible example.

* Set content-type to application/json when creating an annotation in Grafana

Without this change, current Grafana version responds with 400 Bad Request

* Move CONTRIBUTING.md to docs/

* Move BigQuery to docs

* Add example and docs for csv

* Add examples and docs for Graphite/Grafana

* Move installation instructions into a separate docs page

* Split Usage into individual docs pages

* Remove PostgreSQL instructions from README.md

* Add Getting Started

* Remove trailing spaces in README

* Pin poetry version to the same version we use in ci-tools, 1.1.13

The newest version, 2.0.1, fails Docker build. Since the goal of this PR
is to introduce docs with reproducible examples, I am not going to
upgrade Poetry version _here_, despite it being really, really old.

* Add table of contents

commit_message:
Optimization: Incremental Hunter

The common case is to add new data points to the end of the series.
In this case we don't need to recompute all change points, we can
just compute window_len points from the end. We do roughly
2 * window_len for good measure.

name: Henrik Ingo
commit_message:
Fix: When computing weak changepoints, keep p-value below 1

Hunter modified e-divisive such that it first does a pass using a
higher p-value, then filters out all change points that have a
higher p-value than the actual max_pvalue specified by the user.

The initial higher pvalue is max_pvalue * 10. This means that
for values higher than 0.1, the first pvalue is > 1.0. This
doesn't make sense. In fact 1.0 also doesn't make sense because
now every point is a weak change point.

This patch modifies the call to split() such that:
 max_pvalue:   first pass pvalue
 0.0 - 0.05:   max_pvalue * 10 (unchanged)
 0.0 - 0.5 :   max_pvalue * 2
 0.5 - 1.0 :   max_pvalue

Since values above  0.1 didn't really make sense before this patch,
the area where this could cause changes is for users using max_pvalue
between 0.05 and 0.1. The merge() phase should however eventually produce
approximately the same set of change points anyway, but this isn't
guaranteed.

commit_message:
Add timestamp to AnalyzedSeries

This can be used to compare whether an AnalyzedSeries object is more
recent than the set of change points it was computed from. (Think
cache invalidation, even if the AnalyzedSeries isn't necessarily a
cache.)

commit_message:
Replace psycopg2-binary with pg8000 and black with ruff (#25)

* Replace psycopg2-binary with pg8000

psycopg2 is licensed under LGPL that's not compatible with ASF -
https://www.apache.org/legal/resolved.html#category-x

* Replace black with ruff

black depends on pathspec that is licensed under MPL 2.0. Even though
MPL 2.0 can _maybe_ be included in an ASF project, I'd
prefer to simplify the discussion and just replace black with ruff that
is licensed as Apache 2.0, does not have any dependencies, and is
already used by other Apache projects.

commit_message:
Make it easier to call hunter from scripts (#17)

* Pass in Config object to main function

This allows scripts to call hunter.script_main() directly by building a
Config object in-memory instead of needing to create files on disk.

* Allow scripts to pass arguments to script_main()

The default behaviour is to use sys.argv.

commit_message:
Merge pull request #4 from datastax-labs/gbk-harmonise-build

Adds wrapper scripts for tox and poetry, which create a venv, install the respective tool, and run it. This removes any requirement on the caller to mess around with setting up venvs, while not preventing their usage should developers wish to do so.

It also enforces import ordering and removal of redundant imports using autoflake and isort.

commit_message:
fix csv import tests: set unit test data_selector since_time to the start of time

The csv samples are dated early 2021, and the default data selection since_time is set to one year prior to runtime. All of the csv samples had 'expired'. We want to keep the default since_time behavior and not have to regularly update the dates in the csv samples.

when you want to compare only the last point on the branch.

Example:
hunter regressions <test> --branch <branch> --last 1

commit_message:
Finding regressions on a feature branch

A new configuration property has been added to graphite
tests: `branch_prefix`.

If the user specifies `--branch <name>` argument, the data
are fetched from the prefix set in `branch_prefix`.
This works for both `analyze` and `regressions` commands.

The `regressions` command has been modified to compare
performance of the branch selected with `--branch` to the
baseline taken from the main branch, located by the main prefix.

* include change emojis in Slack notifications

* restrict the number of field entries within a section to the maximum of 10

commit_message:
Grafana annotation support redesign (#80)

Grafana annotation redesign

Grafana annotations are no longer pushed individually to each panel.
Now they are pushed into a global annotation list and appropriately
tagged. This removed a lot of complexity and also speeded up annotation
updates by several factors.

The test/metric annotation tags are configurable
in the config file thanks to a new property 'annotate'.

A new command `hunter remove-annotations` has been added
to remove annotations.

commit_message:
New command: hunter regressions

The regressions command compares the performance of the
end of the selected range with the performance at the beginning
of the selected range.

E.g. hunter regressions <test> --since '10 weeks ago' compares
the current average performance level with the average performance about
10 weeks ago. If current performance is worse significantly (in terms
of statistical significance) than the baseline performance on any of
the metrics, it is reported to stdout.

Fixes #13

commit_message:
Make metric metadata accessible in Series

A new `metrics` field has been added to Series.
Knowing metric direction opens a possibility to
distinguish a regression from an improvement. This will allow new
use-cases like e.g. reporting only performance regressions compared to
the previous release.

As a side effect both CSV and Graphite test configs are very similar now
and both require static schema to be configured explicitly.

Fixes #64

A new `metrics` field has been added to Series.
Knowing metric direction opens a possibility to
distinguish a regression from an improvement. This will allow new
use-cases like e.g. reporting only performance regressions compared to
the previous release.

As a side effect both CSV and Graphite test configs are very similar now
and both require static schema to be configured explicitly.

Fixes #64

name: Piotr Kołaczkowski

commit_message:
Extract change point analysis results as AnalyzedSeries class

Returning a vector of change points is not good enough, because
in some cases we want to process change points one metric at a time,
so we want them to be grouped by metric name, not time.

Additionally, this makes code for comparing two time series
or comparing different time points in a single series cleaner,
because the client code doesn't need to compute and store
change points in additional variables.

name: Piotr Kołaczkowski
commit_message:
Remove dependency on fallout (#60)

Remove dependency on fallout

The biggest change introduced in this commit is moving the test
configuration into hunter.yaml file. This way the results of tests
launched from systems other than Fallout can be analyzed, as long as
they send data to Graphite. Previously contacting Fallout was needed to
fetch the export prefix of the test, but now all the required
information is located in the config file.

Ad-hoc (command-line) test configuration has been removed. A test must
be defined in the config file before it can be analyzed. This simplifies
hunter a lot and although it may initially feel a bit less
user-friendly, having a single way of passing test metadata to hunter
makes it easier to reason about. If this turns out to be too limiting,
we may add a way to submit config files (or override config file
properties) from the command line in the future.

Unifying configuration allowed the `analyze` and `bulk-analyze`
commands to be merged into a single `analyze` command which accepts a
list of test names or test group names.

Reduce the length of the target query in Graphite

commit_message:
Refactoring: Extract ComparativeStats from ChangePoint

We need to describe a result of comparing
two time series with each other.
This need also arises when describing a change point.
However the ChangePoint class doesn't make much sense
for describing comparison between two series, because it contains
additional properties like index, time, etc.

commit_message:
Interpolate env variables in configuration file (#42)

* Interpolate env variables in configuration file

Now authentication tokens can be provided in the
environment so they don't have to be inside the
docker image.

Additionally we removed the interactive setup because
it wasn't a very standard way of how one installs
software under Linux/Unix.

commit_message:
Remove change points with small change magnitude

This commit adds a change-point post-processing step.
In that step, weak change-points are removed based on
their p-value and change magnitude. This allows us
to bump up the p-value limit in the e-divisive
part of the algorithm, potentially reducing the risk
of missing some points. In Edivisive, change points
to found later typically increase the p-value of
change-points found earlier; hence the algorithm can
miss some good points.

Fixes #25

commit_message:
Switch to T-test for significance testing

Student's T-Test has the following advantages
over QHat Permutation Tester:

- repeatability, lack of randomness
- an order of magnitude higher performance

Additionally this commit adds Mann-Whitney based
significance tester implementation for future
evaluation.

Fixes #14

commit_message:
Improve change point detection reliability (#10)

Improve change point detection reliability

We noticed that EDivisive algorithm is unreliable
if run on a very long series of data with many
cancelling changes. If a regression is present for
a short time, the time may be too short in proportion
to the length of the entire signal, it may be missed.

This commit modifies the way how EDivisive algorithm
is applied to our data. Instead of running it on
a full series, we apply it to a shorter window
moving over the data. This way the amount of data
per each invocation of EDivisive is smaller and
it can see fewer change points at a time
making it more reliable.

A nice bonus side effect is that this
reduces the time complexity from O(n^2) to O(n k^2)
where k window size, n length of the series.

name: Piotr Kołaczkowski
commit_message:
Improve change point detection reliability (#10)

Improve change point detection reliability

We noticed that EDivisive algorithm is unreliable
if run on a very long series of data with many
cancelling changes. If a regression is present for
a short time, the time may be too short in proportion
to the length of the entire signal, it may be missed.

This commit modifies the way how EDivisive algorithm
is applied to our data. Instead of running it on
a full series, we apply it to a shorter window
moving over the data. This way the amount of data
per each invocation of EDivisive is smaller and
it can see fewer change points at a time
making it more reliable.

A nice bonus side effect is that this
reduces the time complexity from O(n^2) to O(n k^2)
where k window size, n length of the series.

commit_message:
Support for associating attributes with each run

Attributes like: run_id, branch, version, commit, etc
are now associated with each run and displayed in the reports.
This makes it easy to identify versions with regression.
The attribute values are fetched from Graphite events
or from additional columns in CSV file.

commit_message:
Fill missing values before computing change-points

The change-point detection algorithm crashes
if None is in data. Because removing Nones would
mess up indexes, instead of removing them,
we forward-fill the last not-None value.

name: Piotr Kołaczkowski
commit_message:
Fill missing values before computing change-points

The change-point detection algorithm crashes
if None is in data. Because removing Nones would
mess up indexes, instead of removing them,
we forward-fill the last not-None value.

info
